This lab exercise demonstrates a mirrored LED animation using an Arduino UNO with 11 LEDs connected to digital pins 2 through 12. During setup, all the pins are configured as outputs so the Arduino can control each LED individually. When the program runs, it lights up two LEDs at a time — one from each outer end — simultaneously, then turns them off after half a second before moving to the next inner pair. This continues until both sides meet in the middle, creating a converging or "closing in" visual effect. Overall, it serves as a practical exercise in controlling multiple output pins and using coordinated loop logic to produce a synchronized lighting pattern.
